SIMPLE: esculent
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Esculent
<hw>Es"cu*lent</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>esculentus</ets>, fr. <ets>escare</ets> to eat, fr. <ets>esca</ets>
food, fr. <ets>edere</ets> to eat: cf. F. <ets>esculent</ets>. See
<er>Eat</er>.]</ety> <def>Suitable to be used by man for food; eatable;
edible; <as>as, <ex>esculent</ex> plants; <ex>esculent</ex>
fish.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Esculent</qex> grain for food.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Jones.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Esculent swallow</b></col> <fld>(Zo⟦oum⟧l.)</fld>,
<cd>the swallow which makes the edible bird's-nest. See <cref>Edible
bird's-nest</cref>, under <er>Edible</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Esculent</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Esculent
<hw>Es"cu*lent</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Anything that is fit for eating;
that which may be safely eaten by man.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Esculic</ent>⟦br⟧
